{"title":"VLA-ADAPTER: AN EFFECTIVE PARADIGM FOR TINY-SCALE VISION-LANGUAGE-ACTION MODEL","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"VLA models often depend on large VLMs and heavy robotic pretraining, and it is unclear which vision-language representations are most effective for mapping to actions.","method":"The paper conducts a systematic study of VL-to-action bridging conditions by comparing Raw VLM features versus learnable ActionQuery features, and single-layer versus all-layer conditioning. Experiments on LIBERO-Long show that middle-layer Raw features outperform deep-layer Raw features, deep-layer ActionQuery features outperform shallow-layer ones, and using all layers generally beats single layers. Guided by these findings, the method selects both all-layer Raw and all-layer ActionQuery latents as conditions for the policy to maximize actionable multimodal information transfer."},{"problem":"How to efficiently and effectively map multimodal VL representations to continuous action with a tiny backbone and minimal tuning, while remaining robust even when the backbone is frozen.","method":"The paper introduces a lightweight L1-based Policy with Bridge Attention that operates layer-by-layer in sync with the VLM depth. At each layer, the action latent attends via two cross-attentions to (i) Raw features with a learnable gate tanh(g) that modulates their injection and (ii) ActionQuery features concatenated with a learned proprioceptive embedding, plus a self-attention on the action latent. This design autonomously injects the most useful conditions into the action space and is trained end-to-end; when the backbone is frozen, only ActionQuery and the policy are learned. The approach achieves high success rates and fast throughput on LIBERO and CALVIN using a 0.5B backbone without robotic-data pretraining, and remains strong with a frozen backbone."},{"problem":"Bridging VL to action often fails when VLMs are frozen or when the interface between perception and policy is poorly designed (e.g., masked zero tokens), limiting learnability and efficiency.","method":"The method employs learnable ActionQuery tokens that are inserted into the VLM input sequence (rather than masked zeros) so they fully participate in attention and can be trained from scratch even with a frozen VLM. The ActionQuery tokens are later combined with proprioceptive embeddings in Bridge Attention for action generation. An ablation on token count finds too few queries limit multimodal aggregation and too many cause redundancy; 64 ActionQuery tokens strike the best balance, underpinning strong performance and explaining why the approach succeeds with a frozen backbone."}]}
